ive, the beautiful, and the proportionate take their meaning. Scruton provides incisive critiques of the romantic, functionalist, and rationalist theories of design, and of the Freudian, Marxist, and semiological approaches to aesthetic value.In a new introduction, Scruton discusses how his ideas have developed since the book's original publication, and he assesses the continuing relevance of his argument for the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArchitecturexAesthetics. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aA Theory of Architecture.  aAesthetic Theory.  aAestheticism.  aAesthetics.  aAnalogy.  aApplied arts.  aArchitectural Design.  aArchitectural historian.  aArchitectural pattern.  aArchitectural style.  aArchitectural theory.  aArchitecture.  aArt Nouveau.  aArt.  aClassicism.  aCloister.  aConsciousness.  aContingency (philosophy).  aCornice.  aCritical theory.  aCritical thinking.  aCriticism.  aDecorative arts.  aDesign methods.  aDesigner.  aEthics and Language.  aExperience architecture.  aExplanation.  aExpressionist architecture.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aFunctionalism (architecture).  aGood and evil.  aGothic architecture.  aHistoricism (art).  aIdealism.  aIdeology.  aIndividualism.  aIntentionality.  aInterior design.  aInternational Style (architecture).  aLanguages of Art.  aLe Corbusier.  aLectures on Aesthetics.  aLightness (philosophy).  aMartyrium (architecture).  aMasonry.  aModern architecture.  aModernism.  aMonumental sculpture.  aMoral character.  aMorality.  aNominalism.  aObjectivity (philosophy).  aOn the Aesthetic Education of Man.  aPalladian architecture.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophical Investigations.  aPhilosophical theory.  aPhilosophy